Lending Club Loan Riskiness Analysis¶

Final Notebook¶

Aguillar, Fallon, Goswami

Basic structure of the notebook:

Section I: Cleaning
In this section we clean the dataset and get it into a format where we can fit analytical models on it. All variables created are np.number. The one exception is the loan issue date, which I have kept as datetime for the purposes of time series plotting. The three other date variables have been converted to datetime and then a corresponding ordinal number.

Please Note: a lot of the cleaning cells can only be run once, running them twice without commenting things out may require the notebook to be re-started

Section II: Initial Analysis and Visualization
Before running our models, we do some initial analysis on the dataset to better understand what we were dealing with. This is the section where, for example, we learned that the dataset is quite imbalanced. In this section, we also end up dropping all loans granted in 2016, because we realized that these loans have not had enough time to mature and demonstrate their 'riskiness'.

Section III: Model Selection and Optimization
After cleaning, we then fit three models: Random forests, Logistic Regression (with L1 and L2 penalties), and Support Vector Classifier. We optimize for the parameters of each of these models.

Section IV: Final Results
Once we have optimized our models, we use the optimal parameters to fit the entire dataset. Since we are more interested in within class accuracy than overall accuracy, we present our final results in terms of a ROC and Precision/Recall curve, to visualize the relative performance of each of the optimized models on these metrics.

Dropping Variables¶

Justification for drops¶

First, we are getting rid of redundant or clearly uninformative variables.

ID seems useless for our purposes, index suffices as unique identifier. member_id seems uninformative, too linked to individual risk. Drop zip code: state variable smaller dimensions and more likely to be helpful for generalizations. Next payment date irrelevant. Already have information on income, dropping emp_title. Verification_status_joint is heavily NaN and there is already a verification_status variable. Title does not seem like an informative variable and is too heterogeneous.

Second, we are getting rid of variables that collect data on the loan after it is being dispersed. These variables will not help us in predicting loan riskiness.

These include all variables related to loan repayment, interest and principal received.

Creating Response Variable¶

Final Step of Cleaning Process¶

We create a binary variable to mark loan 'riskiness'. Any loan which has experienced any issue with repayment is classified as a 'risky' loan, and replaced with the value 1. Any loan that has yet to experience any repayment issues, is classified as a 'Non Risky' loan, and replaced with the value 0.

In [22]:

Dropping 2016 Data¶

As we can see in the above graph, loans originating in 2016 have not had enough time to mature and display their true 'riskiness'. In order to make sure our data is representative of the actual riskiness of a loan, we are removing the 2016 data from our model analysis.

Section III: Modelling¶

General Approach to Modelling:

1) Optimize Parameters on a small subsample of 1% of the data

2) Graph results from all tested parameters to visually compare performance

3) Fit final model with selected optimized paramaters

Creating a function for choosing sample size for our models. We use a small sample for tuning the parameters, and then fit the optimized model on the larger sample sizes.

In [36]:
def samplesize(tuning):
    if tuning == "Small":
        x_s = x_sub
        y_s = y_sub
        x_tr = x_sub_train
        y_tr = y_sub_train
        x_te = x_sub_test
        y_te = y_sub_test
    elif tuning == "Big":
        x_s = x
        y_s = y
        x_tr = x_train
        y_tr = y_train
        x_te = x_test
        y_te = y_test
    return x_s, y_s, x_tr, y_tr, x_te, y_te

# Using a small sample size for optimizing the model
tuning = "Small"

x_s, y_s, x_tr, y_tr, x_te, y_te = samplesize(tuning)

#creating range of trees and depth to test
n_trees = np.arange(10, 60, 10)
depths = np.arange(2, 7)

# To keep track of the best model
best_score = 0

class_error = []
x_axis = []

tree_scores=[]

# Run grid search for model with 5-fold cross validation
print '3-fold cross validation:'

k_folds = KFold(x_s.shape[0], n_folds=3, shuffle=True)
for trees in n_trees:
    
    depth_scores = []
    
    for depth in depths:
        
        # Cross validation for every experiment
        scores = []

        for train_index, test_index in k_folds:
            # Generate training data
            x_train_cv = x_s.ix[train_index,:].values
            y_train_cv = y_s[train_index].values.astype('int')
            # Generate validation data
            x_validate = x_s.ix[test_index,:].values
            y_validate = y_s[test_index].values.astype('int')
            
            # Fit random forest on training data
            model = ensemble.RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=trees, max_depth=depth, class_weight = 'balanced')
            model.fit(x_train_cv, y_train_cv)
            # Score on validation data
            scores.append(model.score(x_validate, y_validate))
            
        
        # Record and report accuracy
        average_score = np.mean(scores)
        
        depth_scores.append(average_score)
        
        print "Trees:", trees, "Depth:", depth, "Score:", average_score
        
        # Update our record of the best parameters see so far
        if average_score > best_score:
            best_score = average_score
            best_trees = trees
            best_depth = depth
    
    tree_scores.append(depth_scores);

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(12, 6))

    label = str(n_trees[index])
    for index, value in enumerate(score):
        score[index] = 1- value
    ax.plot(depths, score, lw = 2, label = ('Trees = ' + label))

                   cv = KFold(np.shape(x)[1], n_folds = folds[-1], shuffle = True), 
                      class_weight = 'balanced', \
                   max_iter = len(C_list), \
                   refit = True)

Optimizing Parameters for SVM¶

In [49]:
C = np.logspace(-2, 4, 7)
#Guidance on Gamma size from ISLR pp. 352-355 and Hsu Chang and Lin (2016)
G = np.logspace(-4, 2, 7)
max_acc = 0

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x_svm_tune, y_svm_tune, test_size = 0.6)

gamma_acc = []

for g in G: 
    
    C_acc = []
    
    for c in C:

        model = svm.SVC(C = c, gamma = g, kernel = 'rbf', 
                        class_weight = 'balanced', cache_size = 8192)

        model = model.fit(x_train, y_train)
        acc = model.score(x_test, y_test)
        C_acc.append(acc)

        if acc > max_acc:
            max_acc = acc
            opt_C = c
            opt_G = g

    gamma_acc.append(C_acc)

print "\nOPTIMAL PARAMETERS\n"
print "Optimal C = " + str(opt_C)
print "Optimal Gamma = " + str(opt_G)
print max_acc
